b'' b'archive-name: space/acronyms' b'edition: b'' b'acronym list for sci.astro, sci.space, and sci.space.shuttle:' b'edition dec b'last posted: aug b'' b'this list is offered as a reference for translating commonly appearing' b'acronyms in the space-related newsgroups. if i forgot or botched your' b"favorite acronym, please let me know! also, if there's an acronym *not*" b'on this list that confuses you, drop me a line, and if i can figure' b"it out, i'll add it to the list." b'' b'note that this is intended to be a reference for *frequently seen*' b'acronyms, and is most emphatically *not* encyclopedic. if i incorporated' b"every acronym i ever saw, i'd soon run out of disk space! b'' b'the list will be posted at regular intervals, every days. all' b'' b"note that this just tells what the acronyms stand for you're on your" b'own for figuring out what they *mean*! note also that the total number of' b'acronyms in use far exceeds what i can list; special-purpose acronyms that' b"are essentially always explained as they're introduced are omitted." b'further, some acronyms stand for more than one thing; as of edition of' b"the list, these acronyms appear on multiple lines, unless they're simply" b'different ways of referring to the same thing.' b'' b"thanks to everybody who's sent suggestions since the first version of" b'who is maintaining an independent list, somewhat more verbose in' b'who is maintaining a truly huge list at last count) of acronyms and' b'terms, mostly in german (which i read, fortunately).' b'' b'special thanks this time to ken hollis at nasa, who sent me a copy of nasa' b'reference publication revised: _space transportation system and' b'associated payloads: glossary, acronyms, and abbreviations_, a truly' b'mammoth tome almost pages of tlas.' b'' b'special bonus! at the end of this posting, you will find a perl program' b'written by none other than larry wall, whose purpose is to scramble the' b'acronym list in an entertaining fashion. thanks, larry!' b'' b'a&a: astronomy and astrophysics' b'aao: anglo-australian observatory' b'aas: american astronomical society' b'aas: american astronautical society' b'aavso: american association of variable star observers' b'ace: advanced composition explorer' b'acrv: assured crew return vehicle (or) astronaut crew rescue vehicle' b'adfrf: ames-dryden flight research facility (was dfrf) (nasa)' b'agn: active galactic nucleus' b'agu: american geophysical union' b'aiaa: american institute of aeronautics and astronautics' b'aips: astronomical image processing system' b'aj: astronomical journal' b'alexis: array of low energy x-ray imaging sensors' b'alpo: association of lunar and planetary observers' b'als: advanced launch system' b'ansi: american national standards institute' b'aoa: abort once around (shuttle abort plan)' b'aocs: attitude and orbit control system' b'ap.j: astrophysical journal' b'apm: attached pressurized module (a.k.a. columbus)' b'apu: auxiliary power unit' b'arc: ames research center (nasa)' b'artemis: advanced relay technology mission' b'asa: astronomical society of the atlantic' b'asi: agenzia spaziale italiano' b'asrm: advanced solid rocket motor' b'atdrs: advanced tracking and data relay satellite' b'atlas: atmospheric laboratory for applications and science' b'atm: amateur telescope maker' b'ato: abort to orbit (shuttle abort plan)' b'au: astronomical unit' b'aura: association of universities for research in astronomy' b'aw&st: aviation week and space technology (a.k.a. avleak)' b'axaf: advanced x-ray astrophysics facility' b'batse: burst and transient source experiment (on cgro)' b'bbxrt: broad-band x-ray telescope (astro package)' b'bem: bug-eyed monster' b'bh: black hole' b'bima: berkeley illinois maryland array' b'bnsc: british national space centre' b'btw: by the way' b'c&t: communications tracking' b'ccafs: cape canaveral air force station' b'ccd: charge-coupled device' b'ccds: centers for the commercial development of space' b'cd-rom: compact